<h1 class="doc-page-title">Data models</h1>
<p class="doc-page-lead">Technical documentation of COMPASS data structures, relationships, and entity models.</p>

<h2 id="overview">Data model overview</h2>
                
                <p>COMPASS uses a relational data model built on Entity Framework Core. The schema is organised into several logical groups:</p>

                <div class="row mt-4">
                    <div class="col-md-6 mb-3">
                        <div class="card">
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <h3 class="h6"><i class="fas fa-shield-alt text-primary"></i> RAID entities</h3>
                                <p class="small">Core entities for risks, actions, issues, decisions, and milestones.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="col-md-6 mb-3">
                        <div class="card">
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <h3 class="h6"><i class="fas fa-chart-line text-success"></i> Reporting entities</h3>
                                <p class="small">Operational reports, enterprise metrics, and functional standards assessments.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="col-md-6 mb-3">
                        <div class="card">
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <h3 class="h6"><i class="fas fa-cog text-info"></i> Administration entities</h3>
                                <p class="small">Users, settings, lookup tables, and system configuration.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="col-md-6 mb-3">
                        <div class="card">
                            <div class="card-body">
                                <h3 class="h6"><i class="fas fa-link text-warning"></i> Junction entities</h3>
                                <p class="small">Many-to-many relationship tables linking RAID items together.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

            <div class="alert alert-secondary mt-4">
                <h2 class="h5 mb-2">What changed recently</h2>
                <p class="mb-0">The latest schema introduces richer lookup entities and junction tables that allow multiple classifications per record. Risk types now live in their own managed table, risks can hold more than one type through <code>RiskRiskType</code>, and actions inherit structured provenance through <code>ActionSource</code>. These additions support the multi-select risk type feature and reporting improvements delivered in Q3 2025.</p>
            </div>

            <h3 class="h5 mt-4">Key identifiers reused across domains</h3>
            <p>The following identifiers act as the primary hooks between features:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>FipsId</strong> – links Compass records back to the authoritative product record in FIPS CMS.</li>
                <li><strong>ObjectiveId</strong> – optional strategic alignment reference shared by risks, issues, milestones, actions, and projects.</li>
                <li><strong>RiskTierId</strong> and <strong>RiskTypeIds</strong> – lookups that drive governance tiering and thematic categorisation respectively.</li>
                <li><strong>IsDeleted</strong> – soft-delete marker applied consistently so that historical context is preserved across reports.</li>
            </ul>

            <p class="small text-muted">Whenever you design a new integration, check which of these identifiers are available so you can maintain referential integrity without denormalising data.</p>

                <hr class="my-4">

